t doesn’t import it, might the API still be recognized? The agent should capture it. I also wonder if I should create a public top-level bean rather than an inner class, since nested classes require special handling. It’s a lot to sort out!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class visibility**\\n\\nI’m wondering if a public static nested class within a public test class is actually considered public. Since the class name has a dollar sign for being dynamic, the filename doesn't reflect that. I could also create a separate top-level public class called `TestCommandBean` in the same file since Java only allows one public top-level class. Alternatively, I could make it package-private, but I’ve read that `Beans` might throw an `IllegalAccess` exception for package-private classes. I need to be careful here!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_q8nbdqiq7JY557hIl2bsjBAe|fc_0eead3ac69ab1a070169f506a017748190a1a90b6333fd4844", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/jakarta.activation/jakarta.activation-api/1.2.1/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1383, "output": 1273, "cacheRead": 10752, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 13408, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777665674040, "responseId": "resp_0eead3ac69ab1a070169f5068a5e84819087eb7e720ae9741d"}}
